    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>New York, the Capital of Eye Contact</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sam Goodyear letter disputes picture caption (Aug 26 front page photograph) suggesting that New Yorkers avoid eye contact with others holds New York 'wins hands down' for friendliness, openness and eye contact</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Where the Locals Avoid Eye Contact'' (photograph, front page, Aug. 26):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Where the Locals Avoid Eye Contact'' (photograph, front page, Aug. 26):</p>
        <p>Having lived in Paris, London, Athens, Moscow, Lisbon, Ankara, Zurich, Tangier, Salzburg and New York (for 13 years), I take issue with your photograph's caption.</p>
        <p>Of all the places listed above, New York wins hands down for friendliness, openness and, yes, eye contact.</p>
        <p>Because of the myth that New Yorkers are unfriendly, it just may be that the visitor, and not the ''local,'' is avoiding the eye contact. Why not open your eyes good and wide?</p>
        <p>SAM GOODYEAR  Springfield Center, N.Y.  Aug. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
